A '''production quota''' is a goal for the [[Production (economics)|production]] of a [[good (economics)|good]]. It is typically set by a government or an organization, and can be applied to an individual worker, firm, industry or country. Quotas can be set high to encourage production, or can be used to restrict production to [[Price controls|support a certain price level]].<ref> {{cite book |first1=Michael |last1=Parkin |first2=Melanie |last2=Powell |first3=Kent |last3=Matthews |title=Economics |url= https://books.google.com/books?id=Kp6Ls7j3tVIC&pg=PA134 |accessdate=2009-03-25 |year=2007 |publisher= Pearson Education |ISBN =0-13-204122-7 |page=134 }} </ref>
==Criticism== Quotas, like other trade restrictions, are typically used to benefit the producers of a good at the expense of consumers in that economy. Possible effects include [[Political corruption|corruption]] (bribes to increase a quota allocation) or [[smuggling]] (concealed actions to exceed a quota). Quotas are considered to be less economically efficient than [[tariff]]s, which in turn are less economically efficient than [[free trade]].{{Citation needed|date=March 2011}}
==Examples== *[[Oil production]] by [[OPEC]] *[[Common Agricultural Policy]] by the [[European Union]] *A 10-percent increase in production quotas for construction workers triggered the [[Uprising of 1953 in East Germany]].
==See also== *[[Import quota]] *[[Individual fishing quota]] *[[Planned economy]]
